Abstract = {This paper investigates the potential of using satellite remote sensing as a tool for assisting environmental impact (EIA) and risk assessment (RA) studies. Environmental impact and risk assessment is now an integral part and pre-requisite part of most of the environmental studies. The large-scale spatial, spectral satellite remote sensing data provide a tool for environmental impact and risk assessment and monitoring of several environmental widespread activities. Satellite remote sensing data enables the identification, delineating and monitoring of pollution sources, distribution of affected areas including derelict land and surface land use, detection of pollution sources due to landfill and mine activities etc. The lack of environmental legal requirements and environmental management programme relating to environmental impact and risk assessment in the past years, explores the need for using cost-effective tools for applying such techniques. Satellites through their continuous coverage of the globe provide essential information that can lead to rapid and effective detection and interpretation of many hazard and impacts. Medium and high-resolution satellite remote sensing data can improve hazard detection and analysis. They can be used to observe, map, assess and monitor features and phenomena on the earth's surface. EIA and RA in conjunction with the use of satellite remote sensing data can be used to predict the environmental consequences of any development project; ensure that the potential problems are foreseen and addressed at an early stage in project planning and design; and finally enables us in carrying out Environmental Cost-Benefit Analysis of projects at an initial stage. Indeed, this paper describes several studies in which satellite remote sensing has been used to assist the implementation of EIA and RI in several geographical regions such as Cyprus and Greece. Such studies includes: public health problems due to laying of high transmis