Abstract = {The RadarLink project proposes to develop an optimal system architecture, which will implement and demonstrate a data communication service tailored to meet the needs of Canada's Earth observation community. RadarLink will use the resulting real time stream of data to promote the development of three marine surveillance and monitoring applications which have identified commercial and social benefit. CORETEC Incorporated has been selected to participate in this project and will use RADARSAT data to augment existing methods of ice reconnaissance and weather observation. CORETEC's RadarLink application will operate as a comprehensive marine ice management system providing detailed site-specific now-cast and forecast information about ice and iceberg movements. This system requires site specific, real time information detailing ice and environmental conditions. Once this information is received it can be incorporated into the ice management system where sophisticated algorithms provide prediction and forecasting information concerning ice edge, individual icebergs, and iceberg ensemble drift. The developed system will be used in a pilot project to be carried out in connection with the towing operations of the Hibernia platform. The proposed system consists of four subsystems; a data acquisition system, an iceberg system, an iceedge system, and an ensemble system. This paper describes the system development including a functional requirement specification, a detailed system specification, and system implementation. There are three main models to be incorporated in CORETEC's RadarLink application: 1. ICEBERG - A model which can be used to predict the future trajectory of an approach iceberg up to 48 hours in advance. 2. ICEEDGE - A model which can be used to predict the future movements of an approaching ice edge. This model utilizes the present position of the ice edge along with wind and current Information to generate a set of points which represent the future boundary of the ice sheet or edge. 3. ENSEMBLE - A dynamic model which can be used to predict the future movements of iceberg ensembles. Icebergs are grouped together using a geographic grid for which each block is numbered according to the number of icebergs existing in that area. The ENSEMBLE model is capable of predicting the future number of icebergs in each block as icebergs drift and are redistributed throughout the region. The RadarLink project will enable CORETEC to improve the accuracy and reliability of its Ice Management Systems by providing detailed remote sensing services. CORETEC in return, will utilize these services to address site-specific, near real time ice information needs not currently met by others using its own ice models. The proposed project involving the proven effectiveness and accuracy of CORETEC's ice ocean models will serve as an important component in marine safety. Financial sponsorship is provided by CANARIE Incorporated and CCRS (Canadian Centre for Remote Sensing).},
